\begin{exercise}{LIM2}{Graphical Approach to Limits}{0029} 
\begin{exerciseStatement} 

Sketch the graph of a function \(h(x)\) that meets all of the following criteria. Be sure to scale your axes and label any important features of your graph.



\begin{enumerate}[(a)]
\item 

\(h(x)\) has a vertical asymptote at \(1\), but \(\lim_{x\to 1^-} h(x)\) is finite.


\item 

\(\lim_{x\to 3} h(x)\) exists and \(h(3)\) is defined, but \(\lim_{x\to 3} h(x)\neq h(3)\).


\item 

\(\lim_{x\to 5^-} h(x)=-3\) and \(\lim_{x\to 5^+} h(x)=3\).


\end{enumerate}

     \end{exerciseStatement}
 \begin{exerciseAnswer} 

Answers vary. Here are some things to check for:



\begin{itemize}
\item Does your graph represent a function? If your graph fails the vertical line test, it is not a function. This means there are two or more points on the graph that share the same \(x\)-value, which is not allowed!
\end{itemize}



\begin{enumerate}[(a)]
\item 

The graph should have a vertical asymptote at \(x=1\). As the function approaches the vertical asymptote from the left, the function should bump straight into the vertical asymptote. As the function approaches the vertical asymptote from the right, the function outputs should grow infinitely large in magnitude (either in the postive or negative \(y\)-direction).


\item 

There should be a removable discontinuity (hole) on the graph at \(x=3\) (indicated by an open circle on the graph at this point). The function should, however, be defined at \(x=3\), so a point should appear on the graph at \(x=3\) above or below the hole in the graph.


\item 

There is a jump discontinuity at \(x=5\) with the graph approaching the point \((5,-3)\) as \(x\) approaches \(5\) from the left and approaching the point \((5,3)\) as \(x\) approaches \(5\) from the right.


\end{enumerate}

     \end{exerciseAnswer}
 \end{exercise}

